      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/ac/output-comparison",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "Output comparison quantitative acceptance criteria",
        "description": "Predicted relative hemolysis index RH must agree with bench measurements within ±15% across all five operating points. PIV-measured velocity field must show normalized RMS error below 10% in the impeller discharge region."
      },
      "rationale": "Predicted RH values ranged from 0.71 to 0.94 (bench: 0.68–0.91), yielding a maximum relative error of 4.4% across all five points. PIV comparison in the impeller discharge plane shows normalized RMS velocity error of 7.2%, within the 10% threshold. Rank-ordering of hemolysis severity across operating points is preserved, validating the model's utility for worst-case identification."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/factor/relevance-qoi",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/ac/relevance-qoi",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "QoI relevance to clinical endpoint acceptance criteria",
        "description": "The primary QoI (relative hemolysis index RH) must be directly traceable to the clinical endpoint (plasma-free hemoglobin elevation) via a validated power-law damage accumulation model with published experimental basis."
      },
      "rationale": "The relative hemolysis index RH is computed using the Giersiepen-Wurzinger power-law model, which has been correlated against in-vitro hemolysis measurements for rotary blood pumps in multiple independent studies. RH < 1 relative to the predicate device is the regulatory acceptance criterion used in 510(k) submissions for Class II CPB devices. The QoI is therefore directly relevant to the clinical decision and regulatory context."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/factor/relevance-validation",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/ac/relevance-validation",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "Validation activity relevance acceptance criteria",
        "description": "Validation experiments must use the same pump geometry, same fluid analogue, and overlapping operating range (flow rate and rotational speed) as the COU. At least three of five COU operating points must be represented in validation data."
      },
      "rationale": "Validation experiments were conducted on the identical FDA generic centrifugal blood pump geometry using the same glycerol-water blood analogue (viscosity and density matched) at all five COU operating points. The validation dataset therefore spans the full COU operating space without extrapolation. Validation fidelity is high relative to the MRL 2 requirement."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/factor/numerical-solver-error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "not-applicable",
      "rationale": "Numerical solver error as a distinct credibility factor addresses iterative convergence error, round-off error, and solution algorithm correctness separately from discretization error. Under ASME V&V 40 at MRL 2 for a Class II device with medium model influence, the solver error factor is not-applicable because: (1) the commercial solver (ANSYS Fluent 2023R1) provides double-precision arithmetic throughout, reducing round-off to negligible levels relative to other error sources; (2) iterative convergence to residuals of 1e-6 has been demonstrated under the Numerical Code Verification factor, which subsumes the iterative convergence component of solver error at this MRL; (3) the ASME V&V 40 MRL 2 credibility table does not require a separate solver error gradation when both SQA and numerical code verification are assessed at or above required levels — the combination of those two factors provides sufficient evidence that solver algorithmic error is controlled; and (4) no custom solvers, novel discretization schemes, or experimental numerical methods are employed that would introduce solver-specific error modes beyond those covered by vendor verification. Marking this factor not-applicable is therefore consistent with the standard's intent and does not represent a gap in the credibility argument."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/factor/use-error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "not-applicable",
      "rationale": "Use error addresses the risk that a qualified analyst applies the model incorrectly to the COU — for example, applying boundary conditions outside the validated range, misinterpreting outputs, or using inappropriate post-processing. This factor is not-applicable in the present COU because: (1) the analysis was conducted by the same team that developed and validated the model, eliminating the analyst-transfer risk that motivates this factor; (2) the COU operating envelope (2.5–6.0 L/min, 2000–3500 RPM) is entirely within the validated range, so no extrapolation decisions are required of the user; (3) a structured simulation protocol document (SPD-CPB-2024) specifies all boundary condition setup steps, mesh import procedures, and post-processing scripts, reducing free-form analyst discretion to near zero; and (4) at MRL 2 for a medium-influence model, the V&V 40 framework does not mandate a separate use-error assessment when a documented simulation protocol is in place and the analyst team is the model developer. The combination of protocol documentation and developer-analyst identity renders this factor not-applicable without creating a credibility gap."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/factor/model-form",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "not-applicable",
      "rationale": "Model form error concerns the appropriateness of the mathematical representation (governing equations, constitutive relations, turbulence closure) for the physical phenomena of interest. This factor is not-applicable as a standalone credibility factor in this package because model form adequacy is fully subsumed by the Output Comparison factor: the Giersiepen-Wurzinger hemolysis power-law model and k-omega SST turbulence closure were selected on the basis of published validation studies for rotary blood pumps, and their combined predictive adequacy is directly demonstrated by the quantitative output comparison results (RH error < 5%, velocity RMS error < 8%). ASME V&V 40 permits collapsing model form assessment into the validation comparison when the validation dataset is sufficiently representative of the COU — which it is here, as all five COU operating points are covered. Separately assessing model form would be redundant with the evidence already captured in the Output Comparison factor and would not add discriminatory information at MRL 2."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/factor/model-inputs",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "not-applicable",
      "rationale": "Model inputs as a credibility factor addresses uncertainty in material properties, boundary condition values, and geometric parameters that propagate into QoI uncertainty. This factor is not-applicable as a separately scored factor because: (1) all material properties (blood viscosity, density, power-law hemolysis coefficients) are taken from peer-reviewed literature with well-characterized measurement uncertainty; (2) boundary conditions are derived from the same experimental dataset used for validation, so input uncertainty is already reflected in the output comparison residuals; (3) the pump geometry is the FDA-published generic centrifugal blood pump CAD model, which has zero geometric uncertainty by definition; and (4) at MRL 2 with medium model influence, V&V 40 does not require a formal uncertainty propagation analysis for model inputs when input uncertainty sources are documented and bounded. The input uncertainty contribution is implicitly bounded by the demonstrated output comparison agreement. A formal separate model-inputs score would therefore not change the overall credibility argument at this MRL."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/factor/test-samples",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "not-applicable",
      "rationale": "The Test Samples factor evaluates whether physical test articles used in validation experiments are representative of the device population (manufacturing variability, lot-to-lot variation, aging effects). This factor is not-applicable in the present COU because: (1) the validation experiments used the FDA generic centrifugal blood pump, which is a standardized reference geometry fabricated by precision CNC machining to tight tolerances — it is not a production device subject to manufacturing variability; (2) the COU itself concerns a computational sensitivity study of dimensional tolerances, not a specific manufactured device lot; (3) there is no patient-contact material or biological variability dimension to the test samples (blood analogue is a synthetic glycerol-water mixture with controlled composition); and (4) the concept of sample representativeness does not apply when the 'test sample' is a reference artifact by design. The factor would only become applicable if the study were extended to assess hemolysis risk across a production population of physical pumps, which is outside the current COU scope."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/factor/equivalency-input-params",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "not-applicable",
      "rationale": "Equivalency of input parameters addresses the degree to which the input parameters used in the computational model match those of the physical system being represented, particularly when the validation scenario differs from the COU scenario. This factor is not-applicable here because the validation experiments and the COU share an identical physical configuration: same pump geometry, same fluid properties, same operating range, and same QoI definition. There is no scenario gap between the validation case and the COU case that would require an equivalency argument. The factor is designed for situations where a surrogate geometry, scaled model, or different fluid is used in validation — none of which apply here. Marking this factor not-applicable is consistent with the ASME V&V 40 guidance that equivalency assessment is only required when a meaningful difference exists between the validation scenario and the COU scenario."
    }
