  "hasWeakener": [],
  "hasDecisionRecord": {
    "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/decision/cou1-cpb-accepted-2026",
    "type": "DecisionRecord",
    "actor": "https://uofa.net/morrison/org/fda-osel-division-of-applied-mechanics",
    "role": "Credibility assessment team",
    "outcome": "Accepted",
    "decidedAt": "2026-04-19T00:00:00Z",
    "rationale": "The credibility assessment for COU1 (CPB hemolysis worst-case identification, Class II, MRL 2) is accepted on the basis of the following structured evidence: (1) All seven assessed credibility factors meet or exceed their required gradation levels — Software Quality Assurance (2/2), Numerical Code Verification (2/2, achieved 2), Discretization Error (3/2, exceeded), Test Conditions (2/2), Output Comparison (2/2), Relevance of QoI (2/2), and Relevance of Validation Activities (2/2). No assessed factor falls below its required level, so no offset rationale is required. (2) Six factors were determined not-applicable with documented rationale: Numerical Solver Error (subsumed by SQA + NCV at MRL 2), Use Error (developer-analyst identity + simulation protocol), Model Form (subsumed by output comparison), Model Inputs (inputs bounded by validation residuals at MRL 2), Test Samples (reference artifact, no manufacturing variability), and Equivalency of Input Parameters (no scenario gap between validation and COU). Each not-applicable determination is grounded in the V&V 40 MRL 2 framework requirements and does not represent a credibility gap. (3) Validation results demonstrate quantitative agreement within acceptance thresholds: RH error ≤ 4.4% across all five operating points, PIV velocity RMS error 7.2%, GCI 3.1% on production mesh. (4) The provenance chain is complete: validation results are traceable to the FDA GCBP PIV and hemolysis bench datasets, with documented uncertainty quantification for each result. (5) The overall evidence body is sufficient to support the regulatory claim that the CFD model can reliably identify worst-case hemolysis operating conditions for this Class II CPB device at MRL 2."
  },
